Clear- 75 F- wind SW @ 5 mph- water 70 F

Clear- wind NE @ 5 mph- air temp. 53 F- water 62 F
Temp. 37 F- ice in 2/5- ice out 4/8
Wind NE 5-10 mph- sunny- with the temperature at 38 F
Water temperature 53 F- 3 days after unusual 7 in. rain
W. temp. 54 F- 10 days after 7 in. rain- (25 yr. event)
Temp. 68-70 F- lake finally clear since rains 4 weeks ago
Water temp. 71 F- looks very good!
Water temp. 74 F- unusual for East End to be clearer than West End (13').
Algae bloom: anabaena + gloeotrichia- water temp. 74 F
Rained pretty hard just before sampling.  Cloudy with a light breeze.
The temperature is 63 degrees F- east - northeast wind at 3-5 mph- calm- foggy- and overcast.
The temperature is 69 degrees F- sunny day- and a southwest wind.
Clear- slight breeze from the northwest- few geese on the lake.
Cloudy- very humid day- and wind from southwest at about 8 mph.
North wind at 4 mph- partly cloudy- and low humidity.
The temperature is 70 degrees F- calm with a blue sky.
North-northwest wind at 8-10 mph- steady- not gusty- air is clear- humidity is very low.  The air temperature is 78 degrees F.
Calm- north wind- sunny but high clouds- cold air coming in from Canada had arrived- still very light wind as we finished.
Clear- 73 degrees- wind SW 7-10 mph.  Plankton tow showed algae bloom- lots of daphnia.
Cloudy- NE wind- 7-10 mph- after 2 days of rain and storms.
Partly cloudy- 85 degrees- algae bloom- some weeds on surface- wind is SW @ 8-10 mph
Sunny- clear- and southwest wind at 8-10 mph.  Water temperature is 74 degrees Fahrenheit.
Partly cloudy- calm and humid- 86 degrees
Wind is from the west at 8 mph- clouds are moving in- and minor algae bloom.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 42.  Sunny with a few clouds- calm northwest wind at 6-8 mph- light wind.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 50.  The air temperature is 65- sunny with a calm north wind at 6 mph.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 54.  The air temperature is 64 degrees- sunny with a calm east wind at 4 mph.
The air temperature is 71 degrees- the water surface temperature is 58 degrees- sunny with a light wind and no clouds.  Rained Saturday evening and Sunday and Monday.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 72.  The air temperature is 84 degrees- sunny with a calm southwest wind at 4-6 mph.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 64.  The air temperature is 65 degrees- sunny and calm- cottonwood seeds on water surface- floating filamentous algae- and lots of daphia with embryos.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 76.5.  The air temperature is 99 degrees- sunny with a calm west wind at 5 mph but changing in velocity- shallow water clearing.  Oscillatoria and p. crispus floating.

Surface water temp. deg. F = 73.5.  The air temperature is 88 degrees- the water clarity is clearing up- hazy but dark clouds- southeast wind calm at 15 mph- nine days of 90 degrees temperature- 14 days without rain until 0.5 inches of rain this afternoon
Surface water temp. degrees. F = 74.  The air temperature is 85 degrees- sunny- calm southeast wind at 6 mph- small mat of blooming ranunculus sp. ephippia!
Surface water temp. degrees. F = 80.  The air temperature is 85 degrees- sunny- calm southwest wind at 5 mph- mini drought and heat continues.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 76.  The air temperature is 72.5 degrees- sunny and calm.

Surface water temp. degrees F = 75.5.  The air temperature is 72.5 degrees- cloudy with northwest wind at 10-15 mph- later on the temperature was 90 degrees- rained 1" at night- turbid brown water in morning but cleared later on in the morning.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 77.  The air temperature is 78 degrees- calm- humid- cloudy- with several showers earlier today- the white bass stomachs are full of daphnia given by mike Norton.

Surface water temp. degrees F = 77.5.  The air temperature is 86 degrees- calm- humid- cloudy- and hot.  Earlier this morning was foggy- ephippia- gleotrichia- botryofcoccus- anabaena- colonia rotifers- etc.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 78. the air temperature is 77 degrees- calm- cloudy- light and variable winds- many gull feathers floating in the water.
The air temp. is 74- water temp 75 degrees- low gray white clouds coming wind at 10 mph.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 75.5.  The air temperature is 88 degrees- clear and sunny- west-northwest wind at 12 mph.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 78.  The air temperature is 85 degrees- sunny and hot- heavy wind on September 2 and lots of floating leaves- etc.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 69.  The air temp is 62 degrees- sunny with many clouds in the east- northeast wind at 2 mph- floating gull feathers in the water.
Surface water temp. degrees F = 67.5.  The air temp. is 66 degrees- north wind at 5 mph- sunny.
The air temp. is 73 and the water temp. is 72 degrees- sunny- west wind at 3 mph.

The air temp. is 67 degrees- the water temp is 61.5 degrees- sunny- cloudless and calm- stormed the day before so the water is brown near the shore; there is a blue green bloom- coots- gull feathers- aquatic-plants- and white foam floating on the lake.
Calm and sunny after several days of high winds.  Frost in am.  Lots of filamentous algae floating and attached to rocks and plants.  Weed harvesting.  The surface water temperature is 54 degrees.
Low clouds.  2 mph N wind after calm morning.  Many invertebrates and algae in plankton tow.  The surface water temperature is 59 degrees.
Clear and sunny after morning fog.  The surface water temperature is 63 degrees.
Clear and sunny.  Wind ca. 5 mph from west.  Conifer pollen.  Ranunculus after several skimpy years.  The surface water temperature is 69.5 degrees.
Six inches rain Sun-Wed. = brown and also red colored water (custer 10).  Lots of debris floating in lake.  The surface water temperature is 62 degrees.
Calm with variable wind.  Sunny with clouds.  The surface water temperature is 68 degrees.
Floating filamentous algae and aquatic plants at surface.  The surface water temperature is 68 degrees.
Sunny- W wind ca 1-4 mph.  Deep water clearing.  Daphnia ephippia all over surface.  Some shallow clearer but very murky east end shallow.  The surface water temperature is 77 degrees.
Sunny- some wind.  Ephippia thick at shore- ranunculus blooming and lots of floating- broken p. crispus- etc.  The surface water temperature is 77 degrees.
Perception is 1.5.  Sunny- SW wind ca 5 mph.  No plankton tow as microscope cleaned.  The surface water temperature is 74 degrees.
Sunny with very light SE wind.  Ephippia in clumps along shore.  The surface water temperature is 72 degrees.
N. wind @ 5 mph- beautiful white clouds- sunny and calm.
Mainly cloudy- calm with N wind ca 3 mph.  Blue-greens abundant.  The surface water temperature is 72 degrees.
Sunny with SE wind ca 4 mph.  The surface water temperature is 74 degrees.
Calm- sunny- some algae.  Sunny with N wind ca 5-8 mph.  Usual blue-greens- greens- diatoms- etc.  Observed anabaena bloom August 11.  The surface water temperature is 77 degrees.
Sunny and calm.  The surface water temperature is 76 degrees.
Quiet  hazy with clouds moving in wind = very light (for 3rd day) very cool night.  Gull feathers- very few boats.  Vallisneria female flowers.
Very calm- warm- cool nights- high pressure- no wind.

Hazy sun and very light wind.  No rain for ca 2 weeks.  Mounted Eurasian milfoil's tops with roots- even while attached to plants (photos too).  Aqweed stops.  The surface water temperature is 76.5 degrees.
Hazy- cloudy and W wind ca 6 mph.  No wind and or rain for many days.  Floating chopped aquatic plants- white foam- gull feathers- oscillatoria.  The surface water temperature is 76 degrees.

Sunny- cloudless and very light N wind after several days and nights = windy- cloudy and cool.  No frost yet throughout water i.e. not a surface bloom.  Aba harbor- filamentous algae- incredible for that time of year!!

Perception is 1.5.  Hazy sun with S wind 6-8 mph.  No rain of significance since August 22 (1 inch).  Foam decaying- broken floating plants- especially in Dartford Bay.  The surface water temperature is 74 degrees.
Calm- cloudy + hazy- ducks- oil scum- mayflies- algae- May was very dry- 28th rain all night- air temp 64- surf temp 47 (F).
Calm- partly cloudy- aquaweed is working- air temp 77 F- surface temp is 57 F- inlet color cluster = 5
Sunny with east wind @ 3 mph- yellow scum = conifer pollen- air temp = 84 F- surface temperature is 63 F.
Calm- carp spawning along shore- sunny with NW wind @ 2 mph- custer = 3 @ north-side pier.  Air temp=77- surf temp = 70
Calm- sunny + hazy with high clouds- NE wind @ 3 mph- filamentous algae = rocks and plants- water lilies blooming- air temp = 69- surface temp = 66.5
Sunny with N wind @ 8 mph- ranunculus in bloom- broken p crispus floating- air temp = 76- surface temp = 76
Calm- sunny- a few clouds coming.  2nd drowned body found- searching scuba divers only had 6 ft visibility last week. air temp = 78- surface temp = 76
Calm and sunny. north wind at 1 mph.  Cool night in the 50's.
Calm- shallow water clearing up.  Floating oscillatoria.  Air temp 68 and surface temp = 74
Hazy- W wind @ 10mph.  Blue greens and epphia or daphnia.  Air temp = 88- surface temp = 76
Hazy- calm with variable winds- bullrushes marked today in Norwegian bay (sensitive site)- air temperature = 74- surface temp = 74).
Cloudy and calm- inlet cluster = 9- gulls molting- floating aquatics pulled out with roots by motorboats- air temp = 77- surface temp = 76
Calm- cloudy with rain showers around.  It was raining earlier.  Air temp = 72- water temp = 76.5
Sunny with white clouds- SW wind @ 8 mph.  Air temp = 80- surface temp = 76
Sunny with scattered clouds- WNW wind @ 4 mph- air temp = 72- surface temp = 72
Sunny after sat an sun rains- SE wind @ 2 mph- feathers and aquatic plants floating- no aquatic plants visible at many piers.  Air temp = 63.5- surface temp = 69.
Hazy and mainly cloudy- W winds @ 5 mph- high humidity. air temp = 74- surface temp = 71.
Many clouds- light and variable NE wind. Aquatic weed equipment out after Labor Day. Air temp = 73- surface temp = 70
Sunny with scattered clouds- north wind at 12 mph. air temperature  is 72 degrees- and the surface temperature is 69 degrees.
Very cloudy and humid. heavy winds and rain day before. W wind @ 6-8 mph. returning ducks (coots ) and geese heard.  Air temp = 74.5- surface temp = 69.
Sunny with light wind- air temp = 76- surface temp = 64.5.
Calm with west wind 2 mph.  Blue sky w/ small clouds to north.  Filamentous algae abundant!  May dry until 6/28-31.  Air temp 84 degrees. F- water temp 66.5 degrees. F.

Cool and clear sky with 4 mph NW wind. aqweed on lake.  Dense p.crispus in flower in Beyers Cove.  Many carp!! Ca. 60 geese flying low.  West end of bulrushes = almost as tall as buoys.  Aba swimming pier in.
Calm with hazy clouds.  Air temp 76 degrees. F- water temp 65 degrees F.
Hazy partly cloudy.  Air temp 80 degrees. F- water temp 68 degrees F.
Many floating- broken p. crispus + other aquatic plants and algae.  Air temp 73 degrees F- water temp 73 degrees F.

SE wind ca. 5 mph.  Sunny + cloudless.  Surface bloom.  Shallow water at pier = clear.  Filamentous algae on rocks and plants.  Deeper mid-north-shore macrophytes leaning to west.  High wind day before.  Air temp 79.5 degrees F- water temp 76 deg. F.

Calm and sunny.  Lots of floating filamentous algae- including oscillatoria and also macrophytes.  Ranunculus blooming and also noticed these flowers time before this.  Air temp 80 degrees F- water temp 78 degrees F.
Calm and no wind for senior girls sailboat races in am.  Low clouds and sun only at noon.  Many ephippia.  Tiny black dots on dead inverts.  Air temp 77 degrees F- water temp 76 degrees F.
Calm with slight- variable winds.  Sunny without clouds.  Many motorboats and motorboat slop.  Many ephippia on shallow water surfaces.  Air temp 80 degrees F- water temp 77 degrees F.
Sunny with north-northeast wind 7-10 mph.  Many broken and chopped aquatic plants.  Air temp 82 degrees F- water temp 81 degrees F.

South wind ca. 3 mph.  Very sunny with a few cirrus clouds to northeast.  Water much clearer at dock where aquatic plants = scarce.  Clear to  greater than  8 Ft. depth.  Deep-water photos of foam + floating veg. today.  Air temp 79.5 deg. F- water temp 76 deg. F.

Foggy- misty with 90% humidity.  Only brief sun through low clouds.  South wind ca. 7 mph.  Inlet water very brownish and Secchi = 3.5 at 5.5 ft. depth.  Heavy rains Wednesday evening + some Thursday.  Air temp 77 deg. F- water temp 73 deg. F.

Calm with some hazy clouds and blue skies.  Feathers from molting gulls (counted estimated 350 gulls near this date)- female wild celery flowers in Wood's Bay.  Air temp. 70.5 degrees F- water temp 74.5 degrees F.
Sunny with variable light wind ca. 4 mph N and NW.  Are temp 77 deg. F- water temp 76 deg. F.
Very calm with light variable wind from SE and N @ 2 mph.  Lots of fishermen in boats.  Two geese formations flying south and very high.  Air temp 79 deg. F- water temp 73 deg. F.

Sunny + calm w/ variable N wind 5 mph.  Very clear in most shallow water near piers. Inlet opening brownish 100 ft off opening @ bridge w/ secchi 5.5 ft + custer 2.0. coots + hear geese. Autumn colors + cool nights after warm Sept. Air 60 F/water 61 F.
Clouds and wind from NW about 6-8 mph
Sunny- no clouds- and wind variable at 0-2 mph.
Very calm and high cirrus clouds admitting strong sunlight.
Sunny- southwest wind at 2 mph- water surface scummy with filamentous algae.
Hazy- grey sky- and 3 mph southeast wind.
Sunny- slight breeze- and small white caps. lake flys- gulls- ducks- cormorants.  Abundant filamentous algae on shore and bottom rocks.
Sunny and WSW wind at 10 mph.
Calm with high humidity and sunlight dimmed by hazy clouds.
Hazy sun and calm with west wind at 2 mph.
Hazy sun and south to southwest wind at 2-5 mph.
Blue sky and large clouds and south and northeast variable winds at 0-5 mph.
Slight breeze and a little choppy.
Sunny and southwest wind at 3 mph.
Sunny and variable northeast wind at 1-5 mph.
Sunny and southeast wind at 4-5 mph.
Calm and some blue sky.  Hazy and sunny during monitoring.
Sunny- breezy- and small white caps.
Low clouds- high humidity- east wind at 3-4 mph.
Northwest wind very gentle and sun coming through clouds.
Sunny and northeast wind at 5 mph.

Variable winds at 2 mph and wispy clouds.  Lake high as 6.8" of rain May 1-17.  Scummy surface: oscillatoria mats- filamentous algae- "junk"- conifer pollen- stellate hairs.  No daphnia or cyclops- and two cormorants.  The air temperature is 73 degrees and the water surface temperature is 64 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 3.0.

East wind at 8-10 mph.  Clouds- cormorant- daphnia and cyclops present.  Lots of floating debris on lake surface.  The air temperature is 61 degrees and the water temperature is 56 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 3.0.

Calm and sunny!!  Water clearer at MJB's pier; bed of EWM near surface.  Beds of p. crispus at Sg. Grove.  Floating: filamentous algae = spirogyra and zygnema- "cotton"- aquatic plants and dead insects.  Lyngbya.  The air temperature is 78 degrees and the water temperature is 68 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Southwest wind at 7 mph and sunny.  Motorboat slop!  Many ephippia over lake surface at shallow and deep waters.  The air temperature is 84 degrees and the water surface temperature is 72 degrees. Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Sunny and east wind at 3-5 mph.  Clouds except for "center" of sky = Sun!  Floating clumps of filamentous algae and aquatic plants.  Beds of EWM- etc.- covered with filamentous algae.  Blue-greens now!  Ephippia!  The air temperature is 77 degrees and the water surface temperature is 71 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Sunny and variable wind at 2 mph.  Blue-green bloom.  Floating: broken aquatics- oscillatoria mats- filamentous mats of green algae = spirogyra and zygnema and black debris.  The air temperature is 86 degrees and the water surface temperature is 78.5 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

North wind at 6 mph and sunny.  Clear water near pier and one carp.  Large school of 1" minnows off City.  Red admiral butterflies.  Lots of plankton!  The air temperature is 74 degrees and the water surface temperature is 74 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Calm and sunny.  Many ephippia.  Shallow at MJB's pier - clear water- minnows of bluegills and perch and carp.  The air temperature is 77 degrees and the water temperature is 78 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Calm- sunny and humid.  Blue-green bloom!  No plankton tows.  Monarch butterflies.  The air temperature is 84 degrees and the water surface temperature is 82 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Hazy with light variable wind.  Motorboat slop!  Bloom!  Monarch butterflies.  The air temperature is 80 degrees and the water surface temperature is 77.5 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Hot and humid- hazy and calm- with variable winds at 1-2 mph.  Large- white clouds.  Variety of many blue-greens- greens- diatoms- desmids- dinoflagellates and invertebrates.  The air temperature is 88 degrees and the water temperature is 85 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Sunny and southwest wind at 10 mph.  No plankton tow as too windy.  Female Vallisneria flowers and long leaves = Forest Ave. and Sugar Loaf Harbor.  Complaints regarding aquatic plants and not enough harvesting for swimming.  The air temperature is 82 degrees and the water temperature is 76 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Sunny- calm and variable wind at 1 mph.  Floating molted gull feathers.  Many ephippia from daphnia- MJB's pier visited by school of 2" minnows.  The air temperature is 80 degrees and the water surface temperature is 76 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Sunny- hazy- clouds- and southwest wind at 10 mph.  Lake steamed early AM as temperature was 50 degrees at night.  Drowning in Norwegian Bay.  Previous p. crispus areas = c demersum- vallisneria- EWM- h. dubia and flat stemmed. The air temperature is 80 degrees and the water temperature is 75 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Sunny and north wind at 3-5 mph.  Sponges on aquatic plants floating past pier.  Floating = foam- torn-out and chopped-up plants- many ephippia- oscillatoria mats and gull feathers.  Adult and immature loons.  The air temperature is 73 degrees and the surface water temperature is 73 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.5 and at 2ft is 2.0.

East wind at 8 mph.  Large clouds and blue sky.  Lake steamed AM.  Geese flying over.  Many cut-up and pulled-out macrophytes.  No plankton tow.  The air temperature is 60 degrees and the water temperature is 68 degrees. Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Northwest wind at 8 mph.  After a cloudy AM- sun and large- low clouds.  Sick carp ( ) as on its side and going in circles.  The temperature is 65 degrees and the surface water temperature is 66 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Sunny and windless.  Bloom = anabaena- microcystis- lyngbya- many bosmina.  Minnows at pier- gull feathers floating- coots arriving- three loons on lake- sandhill cranes and geese flying overhead.  The air temperature is 67 degrees and the surface water temperature is 63 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Sunny- high cirrus clouds and southwest wind at 7 mph at start and later dropped to variable.  Floating = foam- land vegetation (leaves) and clumps of aquatic plants.  East tow is much darker than west.  The air temperature is 57 degrees and water surface temperature is 58 degrees.  Adult zebra mussels observed and verified mid-October of 2001 on a shore station at one launching area mid-northshore.  Freshwater sponges observed around lower stems of macrophytes.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.
Sunny- blue skys hazy with high cirrus clouds
Sunny- blue sky- S wind 8 mph
Sunny- blue sky SE wind 3 mph
Sunny with clouds- very light variable wind
Cloudless blue sky. Variable light south wind.
Hazy sun- variable wind to calm.
Thin clouds at west end- and sun at east end.
Hazy sun- partly cloudy. West wind.
Sunny with NW wind. Clear lake water.
Hazy sun and clouds. Light variable wind.
Sunny- calm with many clouds low in the sky.
GREEN LAKE AT EAST END NEAR GREEN LAKE WI

Air temp. 61 F- surface water temp. 55 F.  Lake level 796.76 ft above sea level.  Sunny- W @ 4-9 mph.  Lake high + flooding!  Lake = "chocolate milk".  Dam repair needed 2005.  (May 1-31 rainfall: City of Green Lake = 12.9"; Green Lake Sanitary District (GLSD) = 14.1")

Lake level 796.72 ft above sea level.  Water color yellow/brown (custer @ 2 feet = 10 yellow/brown).  Perception 5 dirty.  Air temp. 67 F- surface water temp. 62 F.  Sunny- light variable wind.  Lake = "dark chocolate" + Irving Park shore waters = brown with orange tinge (from soils in field above).

Lake level 796.52 ft. above sea level.  Perception 5 (dirty).  Water color (custer @ 2 feet: 10).  Air temp. 78 F- surface water temp. 74 F.  Sunny- hazy- SE wind.  Rain last night.  Water so turbid.  Noted filamentous algae not evident on plants + rocks as usual - this whole season.  Daphnia first noted.
Color (custer @ 1/2 secchi: 2- custer @ 2 ft 6).  Air temp. 72 F- surface water temp. 69 F.  Sunny- very light SW wind.  Floating Myriophyllum Spicatum.

Lake level 796.47 ft above sea level.  Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 2- custer @ 2 ft: 2.  Air temp. 75 F- Surface water temp. 69 F.  Sunny- very light SW wind.  Motorboat slop.
Lake level 796.46 ft above sea level.  Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 2.  Air temp. 68 F- surface water temp. 68 F.  Sunny with clouds and gusty NW wind.  Bloom.

Lake level 796.34 ft above sea level.  Water color (eye) green/brown.  Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 2.  Air temp. 77 F- surface water temp. 74.  Sunny- calm.  Blue-green blooms- denser at East End.  Many floating aquatic plants.
Lake level: 796.42 ft above sea level.  Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 4- custer @ 2 ft: 2.  Air temp. 83 F- surface water temp. 72 F.  Sunny- calm.  Blooms.  Motorboat slop.

Lake level 796.30 ft above sea level.  Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 feet: 3.  Air temp. 82 F- surface water temp. 78 F.  Sunny- calm.  Bloom.  Floating: aquatic plants- gull feathers and oscillatoria mats.

Lake level 796.26 ft above sea level.  Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 2.  Air temp. 70 F- surface water temp. 74 F.  Sunny- SW @ about 4 mph.  Cool nights.  Bloom.  Surface foam.  Gull feathers.  Very abundant plankton collection!
Lake level 796.24 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 2.  Air temp. 70 F- surface water temp. 70 F.  Sunny- calm.  Bloom.  Motorboat slop.

Lake level 796.24 ft above sea level.  Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 2.  Air temp. 82 F- surface water temp. 71 F.  Sunny- SW @ about 5 mph.  Storms night before.  Bloom.  Rainfall: City = 1.2"; GLSD = 1.4".
Lake level 796.24 ft above sea level- custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 feet: 2.  Air temp. 82 F- surface water temp. 74 F.  Sunny- calm.  Bloom.  Clouds moving in.  Floating gull feathers.

Lake level 796.16 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 4- custer @ 2 feet: 1.5.  Air temp. 80 F- surface water temp. 72 F.  Sunny- calm.  Floating: bloom- gull feathers- aquatic plants pulled out by roots and cut into pieces.
GREEN LAKE AT EAST END NEAR GREEN LAKE WI
Lake level 796.16 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 feet: 2.  Air temp. 78 F- surface water temp. 70 F.  Sunny- SE wind about 5 mph.  Bloom.  Coots.  2 monarch butterflies.

Lake level 796.12 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 feet: 1.5.  Air temp. 81 F- surface water temp. 70 F.  Sunny- light SW wind.  Bloom.  Butterflies: monarchs and yellow.  Dragonfly.

Lake level 796.10 ft above sea level.  Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 feet: 1.5.  Air temp. 74 F- surface water temp. 78 F.  Sunny- light SW.  Bloom.  Lake at pier (north shore).  Clear near shore but @ 8 ft depth only tops of aquatic plants visible.  Coots- loon- monarchs.

Lake level 795.80 ft above sea level- custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3.  Custer @ 2 ft: 1.5.  Air temp. 72 F- surface water temp. 61 F.  Sunny- NE about 3 mph.  Coots- cormorant- gulls- loon- geese.  Two Ephippia noted.

BG's (alpha.): Anabana- Chroococcus- Coelosphaerium- Gleocapsa- Gomphosphaeria- Lyngbya- Microcystis- Oscillatoria Spp. floating mainly below surface (like "tapioca"). Gulls + ducks present. Basswood flowers/seeds falling.Air temp. 91 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 78 degrees F. Rainfall 0.9

From now on Ceratium is most abundant plankton. Eight BG spp (see 06/28/2012 data for list) + about nin green algae species. Some piers not swimmable but temperature grand for swimmers. Informed no AQWEED- Inc. harvester coming to lake until July 16 and GLSD sold transport barge in 2011. Macro. covered by filamentous algae: abundant Zygnema- some Spirogyra- Cladophora + Rhizocolium Spp. Zooplankton + ZM v's abundant. Air temp. 80 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 82 degrees.

Many macrophytes covered heavily with species listed in 07//08/2012 comments section. From now on- observed fila. empty of centents. Pier not swimmable. Floating are Oscillatoria mats (looking like "turds")- molted gull feathers- torn out macrophytes- filamentous algae clumps- dead insects and basswood tree's fruit/seeds. Usual green algae (alpha.): Botryococcus- Coelastrum- little green balls- Oocystis- Pediastrum- Rhizoclonium- Sphaerocystis + Spirogyra Spp. Abun.: Diatoms: Asterionella + Fragilaria; Desmid: Staurastrum. Air temp. 90 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 82 degrees F.

Native macro. are VERY abundant and fruiting; dense beds of wild celery! Fila.  algae prominent in bottom mats and attached to macro. One BG Aphanizomenon; Anabaena + Macrocystis = Very abundant- no bloom. Pseudodendromonas attached to Cyclops. Pelican flock circling. Air temp.76 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 80 degrees F. Rainfall 0.9"

Northshore pier's macro. harvested - finally. Fila. algae declining! Plankton similar to "Tapioca" lumps floating below surface- Gleotrichia evident. Some Certium broken. Some fila. algae without contents. Pseudodendromonas on dead Cyclops. Microscope view of ZM v's identified. Air temp. 90 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 81 degrees F. Rainfall 0.1"
Air Temp. 75 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 74.5 degrees F. Rainfall 0.9"

No BG bloom but slight surface skim of Anabaena. Other abun. BG's: Gleotrichia- Lyngbya + Nodularia. Native aquatic plants flowering and fruiting abundant. Earlier large masses of fila. algae gone from rocks + plants. Floating molted gull feathers- algae and aquatics. Abundant ZM v's. Air temp. 78 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 75 degrees F. Rainfall 0.4"

Large number of gulls- molting feathers. Many floating torn-out wild celery plants as roots are never securely attached- some turning brown as they decay. Natives and algae same as in 08/19/2012 comments section. Still fila- algae strands without contents observed. Air temp. 85 degrees- Lake surface temp. 75 degrees.

No blue-green bloom but skim of Anabaena. Microscope shows Gleotrichia "nibbled". Still female flowers of wild celery + floating minute white "boats" carrying pollen observed. Many gulls- ducks and one loon. Air temp. 80 degrees F- lake surface temp. 75 degrees F. Rainfall 0.5"

NO PLANK. TOW. Macrophytes diverse and no pier problems. Filam. algae decline! Flowering wild celery VERY ABUNDANT + tiny "boats" of pollen on lake surface. Low water level = massive beds of this macro!!! Some floating macro surrounded by foam (decaying!) Floating gull feathers. Coots in Dartford Bay. Air temp. 80 degrees F- LAke surface temp. 73 degrees F. Rainfall 0.2"

Few rare sterile rushes emerging near road at Maplewood; photo 12 Sept. 1998 shows very abundant then. Identified as Sagittaria cuneata Sheldon ( ) by Neil Harriman (OSH)- common name is Arum-leaved arrowhead. Turkey vultures + huge numbers of gulls. Coots- sandhill cranes- turkeys- ducks and geese acrive. Low lake results in many floating- broken- decaying macrophytes + scummy with dead insects- seeds and leaves. Air temp. 60 degrees F- lake surface temp. 62 degrees F Rainfall 0.5"
Cloudy and calm- so not good monitoring weather. Surface scummy with bugs and many seeds from land plants- the dandylions and cottonwoods. Honeysuckle- locust trees and dame rockets blooming.

column1: ` Some Spirogyra conjugating.

column2: Finally excellent monitoring conditions with sun- a few white clouds and wind ca. 5 mph. Also motor boat fixed helped! North shore pier showed beds of Eurasian milfoil coming near surface in clear lake. Usually macrophytes diverse there.

column1: Floating mats of cut-off macrophytes included: Lemna spp.- attached filamentous algae (Spirogyra- (conjugation observed) Zygnema- Rhizoclonium + Cladophora) + abundant cottonwood seeds often colored some contents of mats white. Floating Lemna spp evident at East end surface.
Sugar Loaf cove showing almost entirely Eurasian milfoil and an impressive school of minnows!

column2: Excellent day: calm and sunny! Macrophytes coming toward surface with some filamentous algae attached.
Excellent day: calm and sunny although we started out with clouds! Macrophytes growing toward and on surface with some filamentous algae attached.

column1: Flowers/seeds for exotic Eurasian milfoil (unusual in Green Lake)- and natives Ranunculus (white flowers of Buttercup) + Potamogeton pectinatus (looking like small beads on a string for Sago Pondweed).
Variety of visible blue-green algae scattered down several inches below lake surface. Not a ?bloom?.
Some torn-out-by-boats floating mats of macrophytes- seed filaments- insects- and filamentous algae- etc.

column2: Hazy sun found between clouds- with light wind from SW dropping to very light variable wind. Macrophytes growing toward and on surface with filamentous algae attached. Motorboat slop. One loon- gulls- flying hatches of insects- grasshoppers- fireflies and damsel- and dragon-flies.

column1: Some flowers/seeds found on few broken off exotic Eurasian milfoil plants- as well as natives Ranunculus (white flowers of Buttercup) and Potamogeton pectinatus (looking like small beads on a string for Sago Pondweed). White water lilies blooming in Mill Pond on very abundant plants.
Variety of visible blue-green algae particles scattered down several inches below lake surface ? especially in East. Not a ?bloom?.
Some torn-out-by-boats floating mats of macrophytes- seed filaments- insects- and filamentous algae- etc. Terrestrial trees are fruiting.

column2: Sunny- dead- flat calm and any wind light and variable. Macrophytes growing toward and on surface with filamentous algae attached. Motorboat slop. Variety of visible blue-green algae scattered down several inches below lake surface ? especially in East - and along shore. Not a ?bloom?.

column1: Floating mats of macrophytes- seed filaments- insects- and green filamentous algae includes Zygnema- Spirogyra- Mougeotia. Attached to many submersed aquatic plants are large clumps + webs of green filamentous alga sp. Rhizoclonium as well as small quantities of the above green algae.

column2: Sunny with clouds and calm with very light variable wind. Activity of boats of all varieties and motorboat slop was especially bad! Macrophytes growing thickly toward and floating on surface with attached filamentous algae (Zygnema- Mougeotia- Spirogyra). Many more gulls appearing- several hatches of insects- grasshoppers- fireflies and damsel- and dragonflies. Very few butterflies noted.

column1: Variety of visible blue-green algae- etc. scattered down several inches below lake surface ? especially in East.
Not a ?bloom?.
Yesterday - due to wind and waves - the lake was very dirty - apparently with suspended sediments - and many aquatic plants floating and attached near pier impeded swimming enjoyment.

column2: Sunny- hazy- partly cloudy with light SW wind ca. 4 mph. Surface has foam- molted gull feathers- floating clumps of macrophytes ?sometimes looking a little like the ?Sargasso Sea? - along the shore out about pier length and between neighborhood piers definitely impeding swimmers. Blue-greens near surface are Anabaena- Microcystis and Gleotrichia- especially the latter- showing in the East end. This variety of visible plankton- some also listed below- are scattered on and down several inches below lake surface.

column1: Macrophytes growing thickly toward surface between and far out from piers are covered with very large quantities of attached filamentous algae. These are Zygnema- Mougeotia- Spirogyra + especially Rhizoclonium. Alga forming a fringe along rocks at lake waterline is Cladophora.

Vallisneria is appearing among other macrophytes on the bottom of the lake in the littoral zone. With boating activity- this native plant - with its small roots and long leaves and flower stalks- - is very easily pulled out- floats and becomes very messy. Their floating masses have been observed decaying on lake surface on hot- sunny days other years.

column2: Sunny and calm at start. Wind changed from East to North increasing at East end to about 5 mph. Not very good sailing that weekend for sailing regatta.

column1: Blue-greens near surface and below surface ? like ?tapioca? - but not a bloom.
No plankton tow and no Custer Colors.

column2: Sunny and calm with very light variable winds. Surface has foam- molted gull feathers- floating clumps of macrophytes ?sometimes looking a little like the ?Sargasso Sea? - along the shore out about pier length and between neighborhood piers definitely impeding swimmers. Blue-greens near surface are Anabaena- Microcystis and Gleotrichia- especially the latter- showing in the East end and a faint scum Anabaena. Otherwise the variety of visible plankton- some also listed below- are scattered on and down several inches below lake surface.

column1: Macrophytes growing thickly toward surface between and far out from piers are covered with very large quantities of attached filamentous algae. These are Zygnema- Mougeotia- Spirogyra + especially Rhizoclonium. Alga forming a fringe along rocks at lake waterline is Cladophora.

Vallisneria leaves are nearing surface but so far no signs of flowers on their spiral ?stalks? or the floating ?boats? carrying pollen formed underwater among the roots of the native plant known as Wild Celery.

column2: Sunny with dead- flat calm today. Many- many gulls have arrived. Surface has foam- molted gull feathers- floating clumps of macrophytes. Saw wonderful large school of minnows near surface at east deep-water station. Noticed 3 carp and 3 pan fish at pier. Wild celery leaves (Vallisneria) appearing very often in littoral zone all over lake. Macrophytes are growing thickly toward littoral zone surface between and far out from piers and are covered with very large quantities of attached filamentous algae: Zygnema- Mougeotia- Spirogyra + especially Rhizoclonium. Duck weed and skim of Anabaena floating at surface at west station today - probably because so calm.

column1: Recently the harvester came to my pier while I was on the pier and I watched it go around the pier area as DNR recommends. After the harvester left- the weeds were still thick- tall and covered with same thick algae. The mess of thick plants and algae seemed to rise up again and were not improved by the presence of the harvester. (Photo taken) The harvester should have accumulated a large- heavy load of aquatic plants just at my pier with the quantity of them we have this summer. The harvester visit was very disappointing. Perhaps heavy algal quantity is causing problems with unsuccessful cutting through aquatic plants? (macrophytes?) stems.

Will a new harvester be able to cut deeper? And unload onto the transport barge when cutting very large quantities of weeds? Problems persist and abound for the use of this lake for those who live here and wish to use it for their enjoyment. Boat navigation in some places on lake is difficult due to weeds- too- resulting in motor problems.

column2: Sunny and hot out here on the lake! Calm but terrible motor-boat-slop as a Saturday!

column1: Wonderful minnows visible in deep water near surface at east end and also out away from north shore pier. Fishermen are reporting minnows all over the lake and seeking official identification. Unofficially may be shiners of some sort.

Many years ago- emerald green shiners were present around piers throughout lake; one could net bait for fishing easily off piers. One year they all died out possibly due to some chemical impacting the lake water.

Noticed masses of bright green filamentous algae with some bubbles of oxygen covering macrophytes along north shore and these masses are very easily dispersed- i.e.- are past their prime. The main algal species noticed are Mougeotia (some conjugation observed)- Rhizoclonium- Spirogyra and Ulothrix.

Aquatic plants now showing their tops with fruits through the algae are many Long-leaf pondweed (Potamogeton nodosus) and a few Clasping?leaf pondweed (Potamogeton richardsonii). Wild celery (Vallisneria americana) is also abundant. Eurasian milfoil seemed underneath the algal masses in these locations along north shore.

I observed one monarch butterfly flying over the lake surface heading south west and was pleased to hear of a friend who saw more than 30 over several days of driving in this area and toward Fox Lake.

column2: Today is partly cloudy- with low + variable winds. Terrible motor-boat-slop as a Saturday!

column1: The East Secchi is very unusual and I may have been in an area that was stirred up for some reason. I should have moved and tried it again.
Unknown minnows in a large school visible again near surface in deep-water. Large masses of floating aquatic plants! One monarch butterfly is seen flying over lake.

Today it is strange that so very few Daphnia + Cyclops are evident in the two samples of plankton tows at both East and West as these critters are usually very visible in samples via eyes. A fishing guide believes these two listed above show up on his depth finder at 30 feet and the bluegills are at a level below them. I would like to go deeper with the plankton net for a more satisfying ?picture?. I wonder if this observation will happen again.

column2: Sunny with a light- steady wind from NE at ca. 4 mph. Many gulls. Schools of minnows ? especially visible near surface in deep water at west end ? probably those previously identified as MIMIC SHINERS by Steven J. Fajfar- of DNR + UW-Madison-Sea Grant. Also- Ted Johnson reported BLUNT-NOSE minnows during recent SCUBA.

column1: In littoral zone- some filamentous algae covering macrophytes is obviously reduced in some areas when viewed from slow moving boat. Many floating Wild Celery are on surface and clearly abundant on the bottom showing through other plants in the community over much of shallower areas. At north shore pier- Eurasian milfoil (EMF) plants now looks frail and skimpy along their long stems- filamentous algae are more limited and several visible Water stargrass plants are growing in a cluster. EMF flowers appear in shallow areas near City dam. Lake level is low now with dams allowing very small flow.

column2: Sunny with a steady wind of ca. 5 mph. I used the motor to keep both sampling and Secchi lines as vertical as possible which seemed to work well. Many gulls.

column1: More of those wonderful schools of minnows ? especially visible near surface in deep water at west end this time but reported all over lake.
Identification of minnows in sample sent in by Mike Norton is MIMIC SHINERS according to Steven J. Fajfar- DNR + UW-Madison-Sea Grant.

Again the usual zooplanktons were very skimpy at the 17 ft. depth for the sample collections I have consistently used. The Secchi at East end is now much higher (and more ?normal) than last time when I realized I was in a disturbed place ? but too late to do another in a nearby site.

column2: Sky is sunny with no clouds and lake is dead-flat calm. Many of the floating weeds are in mats and some mats are looking brown as though plants are decaying. Wild celery floating in Dartford Bay along the shore often has bubbles around their masses and I do not know exactly what it means but possibly more decaying.

column1: Many molted gull feathers floating on surface from the many gulls. West end had many small insects flying just over surface and dead ones forming a scum on the lake while East end had no insects evident at this time. Faint Anabaena scum (as so calm) and many plankton + blue-greens forming ?Tapioca? appearance several inches below surface at both ends.
Three flocks of coots are on lake and a larger flock is in Dartford Bay.
Mimic shiners spotted at East end today.

The filamentous algae are gone. Perhaps the windy days have helped this happen. What has happened to them? From my slowly moving boat- the shallow water of the littoral zone is very clear on this calm day revealing sandy and stony areas among the aquatic plants. This clear view of the bottom has not been visible for weeks because of the thick filamentous algae covering the massive macrophytes during this season earlier.
Now Eurasian milfoil has mainly empty stems with a few leaves near their tops just below the surface.
Many small-sized shells of dead zebra mussels are visible lying on the bottom as well as live ones attached to hard surfaces and to some aquatic plants.

column2: At start today bright sun is hazy as high cirrus clouds and lake is dead-flat calm. Filamentous algae are mainly gone from littoral zone. Dartford Bay has abundant torn-out wild celery floating on surface along shore in several areas that many coots are enjoying. Many gulls in area often sitting on canopys over boat lifts- piers and besides releasing their excrement are still molting large number of feathers onto lake.

column1: East surface water is very scummy and both East and West show many blue-greens and other plankton hovering several inches below lake surface ? like ?tapioca?.
Some mornings the lake is steaming and/or foggy.

Air temp 80F; Floating filamentous algae (greens); Spirogyra- Mougeotia- Ulothrix- Zygnema. Flowering macrophytes are in Pondweed group: clasping-leaf- Sago + invader Curly-leaf. Deep-water + shallow areas are clear. Taxa are: BG's #4- greens #8- diatons # 4- + Daphnia very active with Ephipp(ia?) (resting stage of D.) Many other plankton observed.

Air temp: 68 F; East is still worse than west in My Perception. Abundant plankton is suspended under surface of water + down to 17 ft.

Air temp: 89F;  Molted gull feathers floating + plankton are visible and are distributed high and low in the upper lake water. Ceratium most abundant of all. ZM Velligers abundant. Many fibers observed. Unknown filamentous green algae conjugating with zygospores. Marl appearing on weeds.

Air temp: 79F; Many floating molted gull feathers- foam- pulled out + cut up weeds- especially wild celery. Floating duckweed is at east end coming from Silver Creek inlet. Some empty filamentous algae. Ceratium most abundant- also Vorticella + Binobryon are abundant. Many plankton taxa!

Air temp: 82F; BG Anabaena spp. + Microcystis spp. are very abundant. Ceratium and Vorticella are abundant. ZM Velligers infrequent today. East end (4) is worse than the west end (3) in My Perception + Secchi shows this- too. Duckweed + watermeal into lake from Silver Creek via east winds. Minnows at n. shore pier. Many pieces of plants + animals- debris- fibers + terrestrial seeds in tows.

Air temp 84F; Lake water very green but not a bloom (wind?). Many gulls + floating molted feathers. Both West + East are poor (4) in My Perception + Secchi di(?) is 8.0 ft at both. Many plankton but Cyclops and Daphnia are infrequent. No ZM velligers observed today.

Air temp: Surface foam from motor boat activity- molted feathers from gulls- and many cut macrophytes floating as growing close to surface now. Wild celery female flowers on their spiral stems visible above their thick mats of leaves. No Daphnia observed at and above plankton tow.

Air temp 72F; Female flowers of wild celery are nearing surface + masses of weeds with large amount of filamentous algae visible. Two carp: one natural and one Koi-like. No Daphnia observed. Infrequent Cyclops and ZM velligers. Lake is green in color.

Air temp 80F; Slight surface skim of light green color is BG anabaena. Many pulled out and chopped up weeds + attached aquatic weeds still heavy with filamentous algae. No Daphnia but abundant ZM velligers.

Air temp: 58F; Anabaena flos aqua is thick showing down below surface several feet at east end resulting in terrible Anabaena bloom. No Daphnia + infrequent (dead) Cyclops. Previous large quantities of filamentous algae found on bottom and weeds seem reduced to me. Near pier are school of minnows feeding on the surface and 8 nice-sized fish with dark tails. Dissolved Oxygen is very good from 2-25 M (high winds for days). Very abundant beside BG above (see June 29) are Vorticella- Golenkinia (in clusters)- Dinobryon + Polyarthra.

For both E and W basin: Lake water very brown. Two hugh schools of minnows in shallow + deeper around pier + several carp! No BG algae. Some Fragillaria + Staurastrum while G- filamentous algae are mainly Cladophora + Spirogyra. Many Zooplankton: Keratella spp.- Kellicotia- Bosmina- Daphnia + Cyclops. Masses of land seeds- small black solids some very sharp (=Echinosphaerella limnetica?) Lake water very brown. Two hugh schools of minnows in shallow + deeper around pier + several carp! No BG algae.

Sometimes sharp- black objects with no apparent cells visible (Echinosphaerella limnetica?)

column1: Today lake is dead- flat calm with partly cloudy sky. Sun seems very warm when present.

Thick floating algae are more extensive as observed along shore and also small patches far away from shore. As before these are mainly the green algal species Spirogyra (conjugation starting) + smaller amounts of the blue-green algae Oscillatoria.
Today lake is dead- flat calm with partly cloudy sky. Sun seems very warm when present.

Thick floating algae are more extensive as observed along shore and also small patches far away from shore. As before these are mainly the green algal species Spirogyra (conjugation starting) + smaller amounts of the blue-green algae Oscillatoria.
Today lake is dead- flat calm with partly cloudy sky. Sun seems very warm when present.

Thick floating algae are more extensive as observed along shore and also small patches far away from shore. As before these are mainly the green algal species Spirogyra (conjugation starting) + smaller amounts of the blue-green algae Oscillatoria.

column2: Today?s North wind varied from ca. 7 ? 2 mph and sky is partly cloudy.

column1: Unlike previous thick floating algae only a very few  tufts of floating Spirogyra were observed.
Also sampled were rocks in shallow water where abundant Cladophora + some Rhizocolium appeared.

column2: Floating abun. GR: Spirogyra + Rhizoclonium are observed. No weeds or blue-greens seen. Filamentous algae attached to shore-line are
Today?s wind is SWW- quite strong but no white caps and sky is practically cloudless.

column1: Surface of lake is very scummy with previous floating-through-the air seeds- tree droppings and many tiny insects.  No weeds are visible in the lake at this time but occasional deep clumps of filamentous algae in shallow areas. Note the weed harvester is located behind island at Hattie Sherwood Park now.
Not a bird seen out on lake today but 3 cormorants were observed last time out.

column2: Partly cloudy- light variable winds at West Station + dead flat calm at East Station.

column1: Surface of lake is very scummy with previous floating-through-the-air seeds- tree droppings and many tiny insects.  No weeds are visible in the lake at this time but occasional deep clumps of filamentous algae in shallow areas and floating filamentous algae. Many small insects seen hatching- circling in the air - land + water.
Swallows flying near piers and parade of a family of geese near Malcolm Bay. Ducks in bay and along shores.

column2: Today?s wind changed from very light to actually dead-flat-calm at west end- but later at the east end was about 5 mph from the SW. The sky had many interesting clouds and some blue sky - so partly cloudy.

column1: Surface of lake in some places showed cottonwood seeds and foam. The ?tapioca look? of many particles distributed through several inches down from the surface at east end as blue-greens appear - plus pollen- pieces of leaves. duckweed- etc.  White water lily is in bloom in Mill Pond.
Very dirty water in lake due to Monday?s storm run-off and lots of tree damage.  By Wednesday- today- lake was much clearer than previously!  Not so much filamentous algae present as seen earlier.
The tops of a few scattered weeds are visible in the lake now that clearer water present.
Zebra mussels are not especially obvious on bottom rocks or ladders in shallow areas.

Very tiny- new minnows are in a school at a north side pier in shallow water; also present are blue-gills- carp + bass. New ducklings in Dartford Bay area and many other birds ? parents and juveniles - abound in our yards- woods and along waterfronts.
I heard that - many minnows present during 2016-17 winter?s fishing all - over the lake.

column2: Today?s wind changed from light SW- to about 8 mph  SW. The sky had many interesting clouds and some blue sky - so partly cloudy.  Motorboat slop was as expected on the lake near the 4th.

column1: Surface of lake in some places showed cottonwood seeds and foam. MANY  particles (blue-green algae) distributed through several inches down from the surface - especially at east end.

Near piers tops of a few scattered weeds are visible in the lake now that clearer water present.  Some have filamentous algae on their tops. Thick beds of weeds are almost to the surface out in deeper water.
A few gulls are present and a family of geese seen at Sugar Loaf.

column2: The sky is partly cloudy- the wind very light (SE) + terrible blue-green scum by afternoon! Dead-flat calm does help the bloom situation!

column1: Floating are patches of filamentous green algae (Spirogyra + Zygnema) mixed with broken-off weeds.	Weeds covered with filamentous algae are becoming evident at ladder of pier + VERY evident when moving boat over deeper water. Gulls are more abundant + a first molted feathers seen from them.

column2: Sunny and SW wind ca. 8 mph with high cirrus and a few other clouds at the horizon.  It is a very lovely summer day with little boating activity.

column1: The lake water is very clear near my pier along the shore and I could see the carp with an orange pectoral fin and head ? much larger now than previous years when it has appeared in my area.

The wind today and over the last few days may have distributed the blue-greens to other depths (see Turbidity on page 2).  Previously (at bottom of Report #10 and 2 days after monitoring) when the east wind had piled up the blue-greens so pea soup developed and the bottom/fish- etc- were unseen! I was shocked!

column2: Today is sunny with few clouds and NE wind ca. 7 mph.

column1: The lake water is very clear near my pier along the north shore with no fish visible while on the pier at various times today. Many particles (mainly blue-greens) hovering in the upper surface of the water column throughout the lake. Each 17 ft. vertical plankton net sample is VERY GREEN and full of zoo- and phyto-plankton! MANY OF THE BLUE-GREENS ARE TOXIC TO DOGS- HUMANS AND OTHER ANIMALS?

Checking the cove at Sugar Loaf I found many tiny white female flowers of Vallisneria (wild-celery) blooming above lake and below are their very abundant leaves. A few mature clumps of Potamogeton pectinatus (Sago Pondweed) are also visible near surface and Eurasian milfoil- of course.

At my north shore pier- besides the above weeds- are several large clumps of Heteranthia dubia (water-stargrass) and lots of Eurasian milfoil. All are often supporting filamentous algae containing mainly Spirogyra + some Mougeotia. Cladophora grows on the rocks along the shore.  Gulls are more abundant now adding nutrients to the lake by their many molted feathers and their excrements. Foam is often on the water.

column2: Today is sunny with no clouds and mainly dead-flat calm.

column1: The lake water is quite clear near my pier along the north shore with very small black minnows anad shiners visible. Many particles (mainly blue-greens) are hovering in the upper surface of the water column throughout the lake. Each 17 ft. vertical plankton net sample is not either as green and or as full of zoo- and phytoplankton as seen previously this season!
Gulls are very abundant adding nutrients to the lake by their many molted feathers and their excrements.  One merganser and many ducks noticed; some coots are present now.

Foam is often on the water with torn-out weeds ? especially wild celery leaves. Fruits are now forming on some masses of wild celery; now would be a good time for a harvester to move in and control some of this nuisance plant?s population by removing their obvious turions!

column2: Today is sunny with no clouds and mainly dead-flat calm.

column1: The lake water is quite clear near my pier along the north shore + no fish observed. Many particles (mainly blue-greens) are hovering in the upper surface of the water column throughout the lake
Floating weeds are mainly wild celery with foam usually present; fruits observed on many.
Both 17 ft. vertical plankton net samples are again not as green or as full of zoo- and phytoplankton as earlier this summer.
Gulls are very abundant adding nutrients to the lake by their many molted feathers and their excrements.  Three merganser and many local ducks (mallards) noticed; some coots are present now.

column2: Sunny and SW wind ca. 8 mph with no clouds visible and little boating activity. The wind velocity increased by at the east end of lake.

column1: The lake water is very clear near my pier along the shore and I could see no fish. Lots of foam on the lake- often in streaks and wind has piled small clumps on the shore. Also foam is very pronounced around masses of floating weeds. Observed many gulls on lake and also large masses of coots now gathering along lake?s shores and Dartford Bay.

Duckweed is floating on surface in several large masses at eastern part of lake probably moving back to their main source- Silver Creek estuary after several days of northeast winds. Perhaps because of the increased wind at east end and the duckweed- the lake appeared murky there.
